Predicting Online Shopper Behavior Using CART and Ensemble Tree Models

Boning Liu

04-16-2025

1 Part I

2 Introduction

The objective of this project is to apply Classification and Regression Trees (CART) to a real-world e-commerce dataset to answer both classification and regression questions. CART models will be trained, tuned, and evaluated, and their performance will be compared against previously studied machine learning models such as logistic regression and support vector machines.

The dataset used in this analysis is the Online Shoppers Purchasing Intention dataset, originally from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. It contains 12,330 sessions of users interacting with an online retail site. The dataset captures a range of behavioral and technical features related to each session and is free from missing values, making it clean and ready for analysis.

Two primary analytic questions are addressed in this project: 1. Can we predict whether a user will complete a purchase (Revenue) based on their session behavior? 2. How do user interactions with different page types affect the session’s PageValues, which reflects revenue attribution?

2.1 Key Variables

The dataset includes 18 variables, with the following as key predictors and targets:

  • Revenue (Categorical, Logical): Whether a purchase was made during the session (used for classification).
  • PageValues (Numerical): A value metric indicating the revenue contribution of the session (used for regression).
  • Administrative (Numerical): Number of administrative pages visited.
  • Administrative_Duration (Numerical): Time spent on administrative pages.
  • Informational (Numerical): Number of informational pages visited.
  • Informational_Duration (Numerical): Time spent on informational pages.
  • ProductRelated (Numerical): Number of product-related pages viewed.
  • ProductRelated_Duration (Numerical): Total time on product-related pages.
  • BounceRates (Numerical): Ratio of single-page sessions to total sessions.
  • ExitRates (Numerical): Proportion of exits from a particular page.
  • Month (Categorical): Month in which the session occurred.
  • OperatingSystems (Categorical, Numeric-coded): Coded representation of the user’s operating system.
  • Browser (Categorical, Numeric-coded): Coded browser type used by the visitor.
  • Region (Categorical, Numeric-coded): Visitor’s geographic region.
  • TrafficType (Categorical, Numeric-coded): Type of traffic source.
  • VisitorType (Categorical, Character): Whether the user is a new, returning, or other visitor.
  • Weekend (Categorical, Logical): Whether the session occurred on a weekend.

These variables provide a diverse mix of behavioral and contextual features to support both classification and regression tree modeling.

The histograms above show that most numeric variables are heavily right-skewed, meaning the majority of observations are concentrated at lower values, with a few large outliers:

  • Administrative_Duration, Informational_Duration, and ProductRelated_Duration have long tails, suggesting that while most users spend little time on these pages, a few sessions are exceptionally long.
  • BounceRates and ExitRates are bounded between 0 and 0.2, and are also skewed toward lower values, with a small spike at the upper bound (possibly indicating maxed-out values).
  • PageValues is extremely right-skewed, with most sessions contributing little to no revenue and a few high-revenue sessions standing out.

These skewed distributions are typical in web usage data and suggest that median-based summaries or transformations (like log-scaling) might be useful for some modeling tasks later on.

We apply a classification tree to predict whether a user session will result in a purchase (Revenue). CART is well-suited for this task because it can handle both categorical and numeric predictors, capture nonlinear relationships, and provide interpretable rules for decision-making.

5.1 Step 1: Train-Test Split

We split the data into 70% training and 30% testing sets.

5.2.1 CART Classification Results

The CART classification model was trained on 8,632 sessions using 10-fold cross-validation to tune the complexity parameter (cp). The results show that:

  • The highest accuracy was ~89.99% with a Kappa score of ~0.587.
  • The optimal complexity parameter selected was cp = 0.0037, which balances tree complexity and prediction accuracy.

This indicates that the model performs well at classifying sessions into TRUE (purchase) or FALSE (no purchase), and the moderate Kappa suggests a meaningful level of agreement beyond chance.

Next, we visualize the final tree and evaluate its test performance using a confusion matrix and ROC analysis.

9 Conclusion

In this part one of the project, we applied Classification and Regression Trees (CART) to an e-commerce dataset to address two practical questions: predicting whether a session would result in a purchase (Revenue) and estimating the session’s monetary contribution (PageValues). The dataset was clean and well-structured, requiring only minimal preprocessing.

For the classification task, CART achieved an accuracy of 90.29% and an AUC of 0.86. The model effectively identified user engagement patterns — particularly via PageValues, BounceRates, and ProductRelated_Duration — that were predictive of purchasing behavior. Compared to logistic regression, CART provided slightly better accuracy and more balanced predictions, while offering interpretability through a decision tree structure.

For the regression task, CART struggled to capture the variability in PageValues, with an R-squared of just 0.059. However, it performed marginally better than linear regression, suggesting that the underlying relationship is nonlinear but inherently difficult to model due to extreme skew and sparsity.

Overall, CART proved to be a flexible and interpretable method for both classification and regression. While it performed well for predicting purchases, its limitations on highly skewed continuous targets highlight the need for more advanced or specialized models (e.g., ensemble methods or transformations) in future analyses.

10 Part II

11 Introduction (Part II – Ensemble Tree Methods)

In this continuation of Project 3, we expand on our previous analysis of user behavior on an e-commerce platform by applying two ensemble learning techniques: bagging and random forests. These methods are built on the foundation of decision trees and are designed to improve model performance by reducing variance and enhancing generalization.

Whereas CART creates a single decision tree, ensemble methods combine the predictions of multiple trees to produce more stable and accurate results. Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregating) generates multiple trees using resampled subsets of the training data, while random forests add further randomness by selecting a random subset of features at each split.

We apply both ensemble techniques to: - Classification: Predict whether a session results in a purchase (Revenue) - Regression: Estimate the monetary value of a session (PageValues)

Each ensemble model will be tuned, evaluated, and compared to baseline models (CART, logistic/linear regression) using appropriate performance metrics. Additionally, variable importance will be analyzed to highlight key predictors influencing user behavior.

12 Bagging: Classification (Predicting Revenue)

We apply bagging to predict whether a user session results in a purchase (Revenue). Bagging reduces variance by averaging predictions from multiple bootstrapped decision trees.

# Load required library
library(ipred)

# Fit bagging model
set.seed(123)
bagging_clf <- bagging(
  Revenue ~ ., 
  data = train_data,
  nbagg = 50,
  coob = TRUE
)

# Predict on test data
bag_clf_pred <- predict(bagging_clf, test_data, type = "class")

# Confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(bag_clf_pred, test_data$Revenue)

12.1 Bagging Classification Results

Bagging was applied to predict whether a session would result in a purchase (Revenue). A total of 50 bootstrapped decision trees were trained and aggregated. The bagged model achieved the following performance:

  • Accuracy: 90.1%
  • Kappa: 0.596
  • AUC: 0.923
  • Sensitivity: 95.6%
  • Specificity: 60.1%

The ROC curve shows strong separation between classes, with an area under the curve (AUC) of 0.923, indicating high overall discrimination.

The confusion matrix reveals that the model performs particularly well at identifying non-purchasing sessions, while still capturing a reasonable number of true positives for purchases. Compared to CART and logistic regression, bagging improves AUC and maintains high overall accuracy.

12.1.1 Variable Importance

Variable importance analysis (approximated using a random forest model with mtry = total features) indicates that the most influential features for predicting purchase behavior are:

  1. PageValues
  2. ProductRelated_Duration
  3. ExitRates
  4. ProductRelated
  5. BounceRates

These variables reflect a user’s engagement and interaction with product-focused pages, confirming patterns observed in the CART analysis.

13 Random Forest: Classification (Predicting Revenue)

We now apply a random forest model to the classification task. Unlike bagging, random forests introduce feature randomness at each tree split, which reduces correlation among trees and often improves generalization.

library(randomForest)

# Train random forest model
set.seed(123)
rf_clf <- randomForest(
  Revenue ~ ., 
  data = train_data, 
  ntree = 100,       
  mtry = 4,          
  importance = TRUE
)

  1. PageValues
  2. ProductRelated_Duration
  3. ExitRates

These results suggest that detailed user engagement and browsing behavior — especially related to product content — are key signals for purchase prediction.

14 Bagging: Regression (Predicting PageValues)

We now apply bagging to predict PageValues, a continuous variable representing the revenue contribution of a session. Bagging helps reduce variance in predictions by averaging across multiple bootstrapped trees.

# Bagging regression model
set.seed(123)
bagging_reg <- bagging(
  PageValues ~ . -Revenue, 
  data = train_reg,
  nbagg = 50,
  coob = TRUE
)

# Predict on test data
bag_reg_pred <- predict(bagging_reg, test_reg)

# Evaluate
postResample(pred = bag_reg_pred, obs = test_reg$PageValues)
      RMSE   Rsquared        MAE

)

varImpPlot(rf_bag_reg, main = "Variable Importance (Bagging-style - Regression)")

14.1 Bagging Regression Results

Bagging was applied to predict PageValues using 50 bootstrapped regression trees. The model was evaluated on the same test set used in previous models, yielding the following performance:

  • RMSE: 14.36
  • R-squared: 0.341
  • MAE: 6.26

Compared to CART (R² ≈ 0.06) and linear regression (R² ≈ 0.05), bagging significantly improved the model’s ability to explain variance in session value. The reduction in RMSE and MAE also reflects improved predictive accuracy.

14.2 Variable Importance

Using a random forest approximation with mtry = total features, the most important predictors for session value were:

  1. ProductRelated_Duration
  2. ExitRates
  3. ProductRelated
  4. Administrative_Duration
  5. Month

These findings align with the earlier classification results, reinforcing the idea that product-related engagement and browsing intensity are key indicators of higher session value.

15 Random Forest: Regression (Predicting PageValues)

We now apply a random forest model to predict PageValues. Compared to bagging, random forests introduce random feature selection at each split, which can reduce overfitting and improve generalization.

# Train random forest regression model
set.seed(123)
rf_reg <- randomForest(
  PageValues ~ . -Revenue,
  data = train_reg,
  ntree = 100,
  mtry = 4,  # Can be tuned; ~sqrt(p) is a common default
  importance = TRUE
)

# Predict on test data
rf_reg_pred <- predict(rf_reg, test_reg)

# Evaluate
postResample(pred = rf_reg_pred, obs = test_reg$PageValues)
      RMSE   Rsquared        MAE 
16.8194838  0.1049213  8.2523320 
# Variable importance plot
varImpPlot(rf_reg, main = "Variable Importance - Random Forest (Regression)")

15.1 Random Forest Regression Results

A random forest regression model was trained using 100 trees and mtry = 4 to predict PageValues, the continuous measure of session value. The model achieved the following performance on the test set:

  • RMSE: 16.82
  • R-squared: 0.105
  • MAE: 8.25

Although performance improved slightly over CART and linear regression, bagging remained the stronger regression model overall (R² = 0.34 vs. 0.10 for random forest). This suggests that for this dataset, full-tree averaging (bagging) may better capture the sparse and skewed structure of session value.

15.2 Variable Importance

According to the random forest’s importance metrics, the most influential predictors of session value were:

  1. ExitRates
  2. ProductRelated_Duration
  3. ProductRelated
  4. Administrative_Duration
  5. Month

These results highlight the continued importance of product engagement and session exit patterns when estimating the revenue impact of a session.

16 Conclusion

In Part II of this project, ensemble tree methods—bagging and random forest—were applied to improve upon CART models used in Part I. These techniques leveraged the power of multiple decision trees to enhance predictive accuracy and reduce overfitting.

For the classification task, all tree-based models outperformed logistic regression, with random forest achieving the highest AUC (0.926) and strongest overall performance. Bagging also showed strong results with slightly better balance between sensitivity and specificity than CART.

For the regression task, bagging significantly outperformed all other models, with a 34% explanation of variance and the lowest RMSE. Surprisingly, random forest underperformed bagging on this dataset, likely due to the highly skewed nature of PageValues.

Variable importance analyses consistently highlighted PageValues, ProductRelated_Duration, and ExitRates as key features across both classification and regression, underscoring the critical role of user engagement and browsing depth in purchase behavior.

Overall, ensemble methods proved highly effective and provide a valuable extension to single-tree models like CART, offering improved accuracy and deeper insights into complex web behavior.
